Returns the amount received at maturity for a fully invested security.

@param {*} settlement The security's settlement date. The security settlement date is the date after the issue date when the security is traded to the buyer.
@param {*} maturity The security's maturity date. The maturity date is the date when the security expires.
@param {*} investment The amount invested in the security.
@param {*} discount The security's discount rate.
@param {*} basis Optional. The type of day count basis to use.
@returns (TBD)

=ROMAN.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Converts an arabic numeral to roman, as text.

@param {number} arabic_numeral Number that is the Arabic numeral you want converted.
@returns {string} String that is the Roman numeral form of the given Arabic number.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#ROMAN | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =ROMAN(10) // returns 'X'

=ROUND.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Rounds the designated number to the nearest whole number; if an additional
number is specified, it is used as the rounding factor.

@param {number} number Number to be rounded.
@param {number} digits Number. The number of digits to which you want to round.
Negative rounds to the left of the decimal point; zero to the nearest integer.
@returns {number} Number. The value of number, rounded to the specified factor or to the nearest whole number.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#ROUND | docs.oasis-open.org}

=ROUNDDOWN.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Rounds a number down, toward zero.

@param {number} number Any real number that you want rounded down.
@param {number} digits The number of digits to which you want to round number.
@returns {number} The number rounded down.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#ROUNDDOWN | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =ROUNDDOWN(3.14159, 3) // returns 3.141
@example =ROUNDDOWN(-3.14159, 1) // returns -3.1

=ROUNDUP.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Rounds a number up, away from zero.

@param {number} number Any real number that you want rounded up.
@param {number} digits The number of digits to which you want to round number.
@returns {number} The number rounded up.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#ROUNDUP | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =ROUNDUP(3.14159, 3) // returns 3.142
@example =ROUNDUP(-3.14159, 1) // returns -3.2

=ROW.!doc:
@category:Lookup Reference
Returns the row number of a reference.

@param {number[][]} reference the value or range of values for which you want the row number.
@param {number} index
@returns {number} the row number of a reference or an error if the arguments are incorrect.
{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#ROW | docs.oasis-open.org}

=ROWS.!doc:
@category:Lookup Reference
Returns the number of rows in a reference.

@param {number[][]} array An array, an array formula, or a reference to a range of values for which you want the number of rows.
@returns the number of rows in a reference or an error if the arguments are incorect.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#ROWS | docs.oasis-open.org}

=RRI.!doc:
@category:Financial
Returns an equivalent interest rate for the growth of an investment.

@param {number} periods The number of periods for the investment.
@param {number} pvalue The present value of the investment.
@param {number} fvalue The future value of the investment.
@returns {number} an equivalent interestrate for growth of an investment or an error if arguments are not formatted properly.
@see For more information see {@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#RRI | docs.oasis-open.org}

=RSQ.!doc:
@category:Statistical
Returns the square of the Pearson product moment correlation coefficient.

@param {number[]} known_y An array or range of data points.
@param {number[]} known_x An array or range of data points.
@returns {number} the square of the Pearson product moment correlation coefficient or an error if the arguments are inforrect.
@see For further information, see {@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#RSQ | docs.oasis-open.org}

=SEC.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the secant of an angle.

@param {number} number Any real number, angle measured in radians for which you want the secant.
@returns {number} Number that is the trigonometric secant of the number.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SEC | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =SEC(1); // returns 1.850815717680925

=SECH.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the hyperbolic secant of an angle.

@param {number} number Any real number, angle measured in radians for which you want the hyperbolic secant.
@returns {number} Number that is the trigonometric hyberbolic secant of the number.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SECH | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =SECH(1); // returns 0.6480542736638855

=SECOND.!doc:
@category:Date & Time
Extracts the number of the seconds (0 through 23) from a specified Date.
This function presumes that leap seconds never exist.

@param {CustomDateType} date The date, as a string, number, or Date object of the seconds you are trying to find.
@returns {number} Number of the seconds portion of the given date.
@see For further information, see {@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SECOND | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example
REM {Returns 0}
=SECOND("1/1/1900");
@example
REM {Returns 59}
=SECOND("11/20/95 8:58:59");
@example
REM {Returns 12}
=SECOND(DATE(95, 11, 20, 8, 58, 12));

=SERIESSUM.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the sum of a power series based on the formula.

@param {number} x The input value to the power series.
@param {number} power The initial power to which you want to raise x.
@param {number} step The step by which to increase n for each term in the series.
@param {number[]} coefficients A set of coefficients by which each successive power of x is multiplied.
The number of values in coefficients determines the number of terms in the power series.
For example, if there are three values in coefficients, then there will be three terms in the power series.
@returns {number} Number that is the sum of the given power series.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SERIESSUM | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =SERIESSUM( rosetta.pi() / 4, 0, 2,
           [ 1, -1 / rosetta.fact(2), 1 / rosetta.fact(4), -1 / rosetta.fact(6) ] )
           // returns 0.7071032148228457

=SIGN.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Indicates whether a number is positive, negative, or zero.

@param {number} number Number. The number whose sign you want to determine.
@returns {number} Number. May be any of the following values: signed number is
negative, - 1, signed number is zero, 0, signed number is positive, 1.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SIGN | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =SIGN(5); // returns 1

=SIN.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Given an angle in radians, returns the sine of the angle. In a right triangle,
the sine of an acute angle is the ratio of the length of its opposite side to
the length of the hypotenuse.

@param {number} number Number that is an angle expressed in radians for which you want the sine.
@returns {number} Number that is the sine of angle, from -1 to 1. Rounded to 15 decimal places.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SIN | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =SIN(.5); // returns 0.479425538604203

=SINH.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the hyperbolic sine of a number.

@param {number} number Any real number, angle measured in radians for which you want the hyperbolic sine.
@returns {number} Number that is the trigonometric hyberbolic sine of the number.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SINH | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =SINH(1); // returns 1.1752011936438014

=SKEW.!doc:
@category:Statistical
Returns the skewness of a distribution.

@param {number[]} args number1, number2, ... Number1 is required, subsequent numbers are optional. 1 to 255 arguments for which you want to calculate skewness. You can also use a single array or a reference to an array instead of arguments separated by commas.
@returns {number} the skewness of a distribution or an error if the arguments are incorrect.
@see For further information, see {@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SKEW | docs.oasis-open.org}

=SLN.!doc:
@category:Financial
Returns the straight-line depreciation of an asset for one period.

@param {number} initcost The initial cost of the asset.
@param {number} salvageval The value at the end of the depreciation (sometimes called the salvage value of the asset).
@param {number} uselife The number of periods over which the asset is depreciated (sometimes called the useful life of the asset).
@returns {number} returns the straightline depreciation of an asset for 1 period or error if arguments are not formatted properly.
@see For more information see {@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SLN | docs.oasis-open.org}

=SLOPE.!doc:
@category:Statistical
Returns the slope of the linear regression line.

@param {number[]} known_y An array or value range of numeric dependent data points.
@param {number[]} known_x The set of independent data points.
@returns {number} the slope of the linear regression line or an error if the arguments are incorrect.
@see For further information, see {@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SLOPE | docs.oasis-open.org}

=SMALL.!doc:
@category:Statistical
Returns the k-th smallest value in a data set.

@param {number[]} array An array or range of numerical data for which you want to determine the k-th smallest value.
@param {number} k The position (from the smallest) in the array or range of data to return.
@returns {number} the k-th smallest value in a data set or an error if the arguments are incorrect.
@see For further information, see {@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SMALL | docs.oasis-open.org}

=SQRT.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Given a number, returns its positive square root.

@param {number} number Number whose square root you want to find.
    The number must be positive, otherwise sqrt returns an error.
@returns {number} Number that is the square root of the value.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SQRT | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =SQRT(25); // returns 5

=SQRTPI.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the square root of (number * pi).

@param {number} number The number by which pi is multiplied.
@returns {number} Number that is the square root of (number * pi).
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SQRTPI | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =SQRTPI(3) // returns 3.0699801238394655

=STANDARDIZE.!doc:
@category:Statistical
Returns a normalized value.

@param {number} x The value you want to normalize.
@param {number} mean The arithmetic mean of the distribution.
@param {number} standard_dev The standard deviation of the distribution.
@returns {number}a normalized value or an error if the arguments are incorrect.
@see For further information, see {@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#STANDARDIZE | docs.oasis-open.org}

=STDEV.!doc:
@category:Statistical
Estimates standard deviation based on a sample.

@param {number[]} args number1, number2, ... Number arguments 2 to 254 corresponding to a sample of a population. You can also use a single array or a reference to an array instead of arguments separated by commas.
@returns {number} Estimated standard deviation based on a sample or an error.
@see For further information, see {@link https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/office/stdev-s-function-7d69cf97-0c1f-4acf-be27-f3e83904cc23 | support.microsoft.com}

=STDEVA.!doc:
@category:Statistical
Estimates standard deviation based on a sample, including numbers, text, and logical values.

@param {number[]} args value1, value2, ... Value1 is required, subsequent values are optional. 1 to 255 values corresponding to a sample of a population. You can also use a single array or a reference to an array instead of arguments separated by commas.
@returns {number} Estimated standard deviation based on a sample, including numbers, text, and logical values or an error.
@see For further information, see {@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#STDEVA | docs.oasis-open.org}

=STDEVPA.!doc:
@category:Statistical
Calculates standard deviation based on the entire population, including numbers, text, and logical values.

@param {number[]} args value1, value2, ... Value1 is required, subsequent values are optional. 1 to 255 values corresponding to a population. You can also use a single array or a reference to an array instead of arguments separated by commas.
@returns {number} Calculated standard deviation based on the entire population, including numbers, text, and logical values or an error.
@see For further information, see {@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#STDEVPA | docs.oasis-open.org}

=STEYX.!doc:
@category:Statistical
Returns the standard error of the predicted y-value for each x in the regression.

@param {number[]} known_y An array or range of dependent data points.
@param {number[]} known_x An array or range of independent data points.
@returns {number} the standard error of the predicted y-value for each x in the regression or an error if the arguments are incorrect.
@see For further information, see {@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#STEYX | docs.oasis-open.org}

=SUBTOTAL.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns a subtotal in a list or database.

@param {number} function_num Number 1-11 or 101-111 that specifies the function to use for the subtotal.
1-11 includes manually-hidden rows, while 101-111 excludes them; filtered-out values are always excluded.
@param {number[]} ref1 Number or number list. The first named range or reference for which you want the subtotal.
@returns {number} The subtotal of the of a list or database.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SUBTOTAL | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =SUBTOTAL(4, [1, 2, 3]) // returns 3 (max)

=SUM.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Adds a set of numbers or number lists.

@param {number} args Number or number list. The numbers used to calculate the sum.
@returns {number} Number that is the sum of the value numbers.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SUM | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =sum(1, 2, 3); // returns 6
@example =sum([1, 2, 3], [1, 4]); // returns 11

=SUMIF.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Adds the values specified by a given criteria.

@param {Array} range The range of values that you want evaluated by criteria.
    Cells in each range must be numbers or names, arrays, or references that contain numbers.
    Blank and text values are ignored.
@param {*} criteria The criteria in the form of a number, expression, a value reference, text,
    or a function that defines which values will be added.
@param {number[]} [sum_range] Optional. The actual values to add, if you want to add values
    other than those specified in the range argument. If the sum_range argument is omitted,
    Excel adds the values that are specified in the range argument (the same values to which
    the criteria is applied). Sum_range should be the same size and shape as range. If it isn't,
    performance may suffer, and the formula will sum a range of values that starts with the
    first value in sum_range but has the same dimensions as range.
@returns {number} The sum of the values specified by the given criteria.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SUMIF | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =SUMIF([1, 2, 3], '>1') // returns 5

=SUMIFS.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Adds the values in a range that meet multiple criteria.

@param {Array} values The range of values that you want evaluated.
@returns {number} The sum of the values that meet the given criteria.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SUMIFS | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =SUMIFS([1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6], '>4', [7, 8, 9], '<9') // returns 2

=SUMPRODUCT.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the sum of the products of corresponding array components.

@param {Array} args The arrays of values you want evaluated.
@returns {number} The sum of the products of corresponding array components.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SUMPRODUCT | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =SUMPRODUCT([1, 4, 10], [0.55, 0.3, 0.1]) // returns 2.75

=SUMSQ.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the sum of the squares of the arguments.

@param {number} args Number or number list. One number is required, subsequent numbers are optional.
    1 to 255 arguments for which you want the sum of the squares. You can also use a single array
    or a reference to an array instead of arguments separated by commas.
@returns {number} The sum of the squares of the arguments.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SUMSQ | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =SUMSQ([1, 2, 3]) // returns 14

=SUMX2MY2.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the sum of the difference of squares of corresponding values in two arrays.

@param {number[]} array_x The first array or range of values.
@param {number[]} array_y The second array or range of values.
@returns {number} The sum of the difference of squares of corresponding values in two arrays.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SUMX2MY2 | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =SUMX2MY2([1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]) // returns -63

=SUMX2PY2.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the sum of the sum of squares of corresponding values in two arrays.

@param {number[]} array_x The first array or range of values.
@param {number[]} array_y The second array or range of values.
@returns {number} The sum of the difference of squares of corresponding values in two arrays.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SUMX2PY2 | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =SUMX2PY2([1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]) // returns 91

=SUMXMY2.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the sum of squares of differences of corresponding values in two arrays.

@param {number[]} array_x The first array or range of values.
@param {number[]} array_y The second array or range of values.
@returns {number} The sum of squares of differences of corresponding values in two arrays.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SUMXMY2 | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =SUMXMY2([1, 2, 3], [4, 5, 6]) // returns 27

=SWITCH.!doc:
@category:Logical
Evaluates an expression against a list of values and returns the result corresponding to the first matching value.
If there is no match, an optional default value may be returned.

@param {Array} args The expression and values to compare.
@returns {*} The result corresponding to the first matching value.
@see For more information see {@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SWITCH | docs.oasis-open.org}

=SYD.!doc:
@category:Financial
Returns the sum-of-years' digits depreciation of an asset for a specified period.

@param {number} initcost The initial cost of the asset.
@param {number} salvageval The value at the end of the depreciation (sometimes called the salvage value of the asset).
@param {number} uselife The number of periods over which the asset is depreciated (sometimes called the useful life of the asset).
@param {number} periods The period and must use the same units as life.
@returns {number} the sum-of-years' digits depreciation of an asset for a specified period or an error if arguments are not formatted properly.
@see For more information see {@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#SYD | docs.oasis-open.org}

=T.!doc:
@category:Text
Return the text (if text), else return 0-length Text value

@param {*} value The value you want to test if text.
@returns {string} Returns _value_ if it is a string; otherwise an empty string.
@see For further information, see {@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#T | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example
=T("HI"); // Returns "HI"
@example
=T(5); // Return ""

=TAN.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Given an angle in radians, returns the tangent of the angle. In a right triangle
the tangent of an acute angle is the ratio of the length of the opposite side to
the length of the adjacent side.

@param {number} number Number that is an angle expressed in radians for which you want the tangent.
@returns {number} Number that is the tangent of angle, rounded to 15 decimal places.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#TAN | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =TAN(.5); // returns 0.5463024898437905
@example =TAN(.5,.6,.7); // returns [0.5463024898437905, 0.6841368083416923, 0.8422883804630794]

=TANH.!doc:
@category:Math & Trigonometry
Returns the hyperbolic tangent of a number.

@param {number} number Any real number.
@returns {number} The hyperbolic tangent of the number.
@see For futher information, see&nbsp;{@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#TANH | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example =TANH(0.5) // returns 0.46211715726000974

=TBILLEQ.!doc:
@category:Financial
Returns the bond-equivalent yield for a Treasury bill.

@param {Date|number|string} settlement_date The Treasury bill's settlement date. The security settlement date is the date after the issue date when the Treasury bill is traded to the buyer.
@param {Date|number|string} maturity_date The Treasury bill's maturity date. The maturity date is the date when the Treasury bill expires.
@param {number} discount_rate The Treasury bill's discount rate.
@returns {number} Returns the bond-equivalent yield for a Treasury bill or an error if the arguments are not formatted properly.
@see For more information see {@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#TBILLEQ | docs.oasis-open.org}

=TBILLPRICE.!doc:
@category:Financial
Returns the price per $100 face value for a Treasury bill.

@param {Date|number|string} settlement_date The Treasury bill's settlement date. The security settlement date is the date after the issue date when the Treasury bill is traded to the buyer.
@param {Date|number|string} maturity_date The Treasury bill's maturity date. The maturity date is the date when the Treasury bill expires.
@param {number} discount_rate The Treasury bill's discount rate.
@returns {number} returns the price per $100 facec value for a treasury bill or an error if the arguments arent formatted properly.
@see For more information see {@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#TBILLPRICE | docs.oasis-open.org}

=TBILLYIELD.!doc:
@category:Financial
Returns the yield for a Treasury bill.

@param {Date|number|string} settlement_date The Treasury bill's settlement date. The security settlement date is the date after the issue date when the Treasury bill is traded to the buyer.
@param {Date|number|string} maturity_date The Treasury bill's maturity date. The maturity date is the date when the Treasury bill expires.
@param {number} price The Treasury bill's price per $100 face value.
@returns {number} the yield for a treasury bill or an error if the arguments are not formated properly.
@see For more information see {@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#TBILLYIELD | docs.oasis-open.org}

=TDIST2T.!doc:
@category:Statistical
Returns the Percentage Points (probability) for the Student t-distribution

@param {number} x The numeric value at which to evaluate the distribution.
@param {number} deg_freedom An integer indicating the number of degrees of freedom.
@returns {number} the Percentage Points (probability) for the Student t-distribution  or an error if the arguments are incorrect.
@see For further information, see {@link https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/office/t-dist-2t-function-198e9340-e360-4230-bd21-f52f22ff5c28 | support.microsoft.com}

=TIME.!doc:
@category:Date & Time
Translates numbers for the various components of time; then returns the number representing time (as a fraction of a day)

@param {number} hour A number from 0 (zero) to 32767 representing the hour. Any value
    greater than 23 will be divided by 24 and the remainder will be treated as the hour value.
@param {number} minute A number from 0 to 32767 representing the minute. Any value
    greater than 59 will be converted to hours and minutes.
@param {number} second A number from 0 to 32767 representing the second. Any value
    greater than 59 will be converted to hours, minutes, and seconds.
@returns {number} A number representing time (as a fraction of a day); display usually formatted in current locale.
@see For further information, see {@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#TIME | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example
REM {Returns 0.04237268518518519}
=TIME(1, 1, 1);
@example
REM {Returns Fri Dec 24 1993 12:30:40 GMT-0500 (Eastern Standard Time)}
=TIME(93, 12, 24, 12, 30, 40);
@example
REM {Returns Fri Dec 24 1993 12:30:40 GMT-0500 (Eastern Standard Time)}
=TIME(DATE(93, 12, 24, 12, 30, 40));

=TIMEVALUE.!doc:
@category:Date & Time
Converts a time in the form of text to a serial number.

@param {string} time_text The time represented by a text string.
@returns {number} The decimal number of the time represented by a text string. The decimal
    number is a value ranging from 0 (zero) to 0.99988426, representing the times
    from 0:00:00 (12:00:00 AM) to 23:59:59 (11:59:59 P.M.).
@see For further information, see {@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#TIMEVALUE | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example
REM {Returns 0.5}
=TIMEVALUE("1/1/1900 12:00:00");

=TINV2T.!doc:
@category:Statistical
Returns the inverse of the Student's t-distribution

@param {number} probability The probability associated with the Student's t-distribution.
@param {number} deg_freedom The number of degrees of freedom with which to characterize the distribution.
@returns {number} the inverse of the Student's t-distribution or and error if the arguments are incorrect.
@see For further information, see {@link https://support.microsoft.com/en-us/office/t-inv-2t-function-ce72ea19-ec6c-4be7-bed2-b9baf2264f17 | support.microsoft.com}

=TODAY.!doc:
@category:Date & Time
Returns today's date.

@returns {Date} The date object for the current date and time.
@see For further information, see {@link https://docs.oasis-open.org/office/OpenDocument/v1.3/cs02/part4-formula/OpenDocument-v1.3-cs02-part4-formula.html#TODAY | docs.oasis-open.org}
@example
REM {Returns Wed Jun 07 2023 12:26:36 GMT-0400 (Eastern Daylight Time)}
